            "@type": "dctypes:Text",
            "format": "text/html",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>LD.XV.R2</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>She acts upon advice</strong></p>\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-e8fcc8ec-7fff-2696-b96c-ccf5818e8708\">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This note corresponds to the original title Dickens wrote for this chapter in the manuscript: &ldquo;Acting On Advice&rdquo; (see LD.XV.R1). Two types of &ldquo;advice&rdquo; are invoked in this chapter: Fanny makes a pretense of asking for &ldquo;sisterly advice&rdquo; about arrangements for her marriage; Fanny offers &ldquo;a word of advice&rdquo; to Little Dorrit that she raise objections to any proposed union between their father and Mrs. General (LD 587).</p>"
